-- Devoteam, Enel, Fiat, Impregilo, Telecom Italia: European Equity Preview
-- B y   N i k o l a j   G a m m e l t o f t
-- 2010-11-08T22:09:30Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-08/devoteam-enel-fiat-impregilo-telecom-italia-european-equity-preview.html
The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in  European  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are from the previous close.  The  Stoxx Europe 600 Index  fell less than 0.1 percent to
271.91. The  Stoxx 50 Index  lost 0.1 percent to 2,603.63. The
 Euro Stoxx 50 Index , a benchmark for nations using the euro,
retreated 0.3 percent to 2,867.96.  Banco Espirito Santo SA  (BES PL): Portugal’s biggest
publicly traded bank by market value was among lenders that had
their long-term issuer default ratings cut by Fitch Ratings.
Banco BPI SA (BPI PL) and Banco Comercial Portugues SA (BCP PL)
also had their ratings cut by Fitch. Shares in Espirito Santo
fell 0.6 percent to 3.35 euros; BPI climbed 1.6 percent to 1.545
euros and BCP rose 1.3 percent to 63.3 cents.  Deutsche Lufthansa AG  (LHA GY): Europe’s second-largest
carrier, which raised its full-year forecast last month on a
recovery in intercontinental passenger and cargo traffic, will
release monthly traffic figures. The shares rose 0.5 percent to
16.34 euros.  Devoteam  (DVT FP): The network-services company said third-
quarter sales rose to 118.2 million euros from 107 million euros
a year earlier. The company confirmed its objectives for the
year and said revenue will be about 485 million euros to 490
million euros. The stock rose 1.3 percent to 20.30 euros.  Fiat SpA  (F IM): Chief Executive Officer Sergio Marchionne
ruled out a spinoff of Fiat’s Mirafiori plant in Italy or
Chrysler Group LLC getting a stake in the plant.  Fiat shares were unchanged at 12.78 euros.  Enel Green Power SpA  (EGPW SM): The renewable energy unit
of Italy’s biggest utility said third-quarter profit rose 27
percent on increased production and lower taxes. The company’s
Spanish-traded shares fell 1.3 percent to 1.57 euros.  Impregilo SpA (IPG IM): Italy’s largest construction
company’s nine-month net income rose to 108.8 million euros from
32.36 million euros a year earlier. Impregilo gained 1 percent,
to 2.27 euros.  Korian  (KORI FP): The retirement-home operator raised its
sales forecast for the year and now predicts 8 percent growth.
Third-quarter revenue climbed 9.8 percent to 237.6 million
euros. The stock fell 0.2 percent to 16.83 euros.  Promotora de Informaciones SA  (PRS SM): Spain’s largest
media company expects to win antitrust approval this week to
sell stakes in pay-TV unit Digital Plus to Gestevision Telecinco
SA and Telefonica SA, Chief Executive Officer Juan Luis Cebrian
said today. He made the comments on a conference call after
Prisa reported a 96 percent increase in nine-month profit. The
shares climbed 2.4 percent to 1.895 euros. Shares in Telefonica
fell 1.4 percent to 18.465 euros and shares in Telecinco rose
2.7 percent to 9.351 euros.  Telecom Italia SpA  (TIT IM): Italy’s biggest phone company
agreed with Bolivia’s government and Entel Bolivia “ending the
controversy that arose in 2007 following the expropriation” of
a stake held by a unit of the Italian company in Entel.  Telecom Italia lost 1.1 percent to 1.025 euros.  Transics International NV  (TRAN BB): Belgium’s biggest
maker of on-board computers for trucks said third-quarter sales
advanced 24 percent to 9.7 million euros and forecast 2010
revenue will exceed 39 million euros. Transics fell 1.1 percent
to 6.22 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
